1.A map of your outcome of interest in point form, with some description of what, when and why you think selection bias may be an issue in your model.

In this model, I use the data of weapon violation. There might be great selection bias in this kind of crime. Because in some regions of the city, maybe weapon violation is normal and if there is no death in the violation, people might think it is not a big deal and will not report the crime to the police. Also, there might be over-policing in some areas where the police think weapon violation will happen more frequently than in other places of the city, hence leading to more violation being dicovered by the police.

Below I read the data of weapon violation and print it on a plot.

weapon <-
  read.socrata("https://data.cityofchicago.org/Public-Safety/Crimes-2017/d62x-nvdr") %>%
  filter(Primary.Type == "WEAPONS VIOLATION")%>%
  mutate(x = gsub("[()]", "", Location)) %>%
  separate(x,into= c("Y","X"), sep=",") %>%
  mutate(X = as.numeric(X),
         Y = as.numeric(Y)) %>% 
  na.omit %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant")%>%
  st_transform(102271) %>% 
  distinct()

2.A map of your outcome joined to the fishnet.

Then I join the weapon violation data into the fishnet made before.

crime_net <- 
  weapon %>% 
  dplyr::select() %>% 
  mutate(countWeapon = 1) %>% 
  aggregate(., fishnet, sum) %>%
  mutate(countWeapon = ifelse(is.na(countWeapon), 0, countWeapon),
         uniqueID = rownames(.),
         cvID = sample(round(nrow(fishnet) / 24), size=nrow(fishnet), replace = TRUE))

ggplot()+geom_sf(data=crime_net,aes(fill=countWeapon))+scale_fill_viridis()

3.A small multiple map of your risk factors in the fishnet (counts, distance and/or other feature engineering approaches.

I choose abandoned cars, abandoned buildings, graffiti, sanitation, lights-outs in streets and alleies, liquor retail and some neighbourhood with top crime-density as the risk factors. For the reason that the blight built environment, liquor consuming and bad neighbourhood environment might lead to crimes. Also, I add a protective factor which will protect the communities from the crime, the police station. In this model, i use the nearest neighbour feature engineering approach. I also calculate the distance to some single point on the map.

The following steps combine all the risk factors i find into a vars_net dataset

vars_net <- 
  rbind(abandonCars,streetLightsOut,abandonBuildings,
        liquorRetail, graffiti, sanitation,policeStation,AlleyLightsOut,RodentBaiting,potHole,enviCompla) %>%
  st_join(., fishnet, join=st_within) %>%
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>%
  group_by(uniqueID, Legend) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  full_join(fishnet) %>%
  spread(Legend, count, fill=0) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(-`<NA>`) %>%
  na.omit()

Then I calculate the distance to the nearest neighbour of the risk factors and plot them on a small multiple plot.

nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
    output <-
      as.data.frame(nn) %>%
      rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
      gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
      group_by(thisPoint) %>%
      summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
      arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
      dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
      pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

Next, i use two kinds of cross validation and make four regression with/without spatial structure taken into consideration

reg.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Graffiti.nn", 
              "Liquor_Retail.nn", "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn", "loopDistance","policeStation.nn","RodentBaiting.nn","AlleyLightsOut.nn","potHole.nn","enviCompla.nn","sus_hopo.nn")

reg.ss.vars <- c("Abandoned_Buildings.nn", "Abandoned_Cars.nn", "Graffiti.nn", "Liquor_Retail.nn", 
                 "Street_Lights_Out.nn", "Sanitation.nn", "loopDistance","policeStation.nn","RodentBaiting.nn","AlleyLightsOut.nn",
                 "weapon.isSig", "weapon.isSig.dist","potHole.nn","enviCompla.nn","sus_hopo.nn")
crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {

allPredictions <- data.frame()
cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])

for (i in cvID_list) {

  thisFold <- i
  #cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")

  fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
  fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
                dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
  
  regression <-
    glm(countWeapon ~ ., family = "poisson", 
      data = fold.train %>% 
      dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
  
  thisPrediction <- 
    mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
  allPredictions <-
    rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}
reg.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countWeapon",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countWeapon, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.cv <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "cvID",
  dependentVariable = "countWeapon",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = cvID, countWeapon, Prediction, geometry)
  
reg.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countWeapon",
  indVariables = reg.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countWeapon, Prediction, geometry)

reg.ss.spatialCV <- crossValidate(
  dataset = final_net,
  id = "name",
  dependentVariable = "countWeapon",
  indVariables = reg.ss.vars) %>%
    dplyr::select(cvID = name, countWeapon, Prediction, geometry)
reg.summary <- 
  rbind(
    mutate(reg.cv,           Error = countWeapon - Prediction,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.cv,        Error = countWeapon - Prediction,
                             Regression = "Random k-fold CV: Spatial Structure"),
    
    mutate(reg.spatialCV,    Error = countWeapon - Prediction,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Just Risk Factors"),
                             
    mutate(reg.ss.spatialCV, Error = countWeapon - Prediction,
                             Regression = "Spatial LOGO-CV: Spatial Structure")) %>%
    st_sf()

8.A table of MAE and standard deviation MAE by regression.

It can be concluded from the table that regression model with spatial structure taken into consideration have a lower MAE AND SD_MAE. Also, the k-fold cross validation model performs a little bit better than the LOGO-CV one.

st_set_geometry(reg.summary, NULL) %>%
  group_by(Regression) %>% 
  summarize(MAE = round(mean(abs(Prediction - countWeapon), na.rm = T),2),

  kable(caption = "MAE by regression") %>%
    kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>%
    row_spec(2, color = "black", background = "#FDE725FF") %>%

# Convert kernel density to grid cells taking the mean
wea_KDE_sf <- as.data.frame(wea_KD) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("x", "y"), crs = st_crs(final_net)) %>%
  aggregate(., final_net, mean) %>%
#Mutate the Risk_Category field as defined below.
  mutate(label = "Kernel Density",
         Risk_Category = ntile(value, 100),
         Risk_Category = case_when(
           Risk_Category >= 90 ~ "90% to 100%",
           Risk_Category >= 70 & Risk_Category <= 89 ~ "70% to 89%",
           Risk_Category >= 50 & Risk_Category <= 69 ~ "50% to 69%",
           Risk_Category >= 30 & Risk_Category <= 49 ~ "30% to 49%",
           Risk_Category >= 1 & Risk_Category <= 29 ~ "1% to 29%")) %>%
#Bind to a layer where test set crime counts are spatially joined to the fisnnet.
  bind_cols(
    aggregate(
      dplyr::select(weapon) %>% mutate(weaponCount = 1), ., length) %>%
    mutate(weaponCount = replace_na(weaponCount, 0))) %>%
#Select the fields we need
  dplyr::select(label, Risk_Category, weaponCount)

12.Two paragraphs on why or why not you would recommend your algorithm be put into production.

Personally speaking, I will not recommend my algorithm or put it into production. Although comparing with the kernel density prediction, my predictions do capture more observed weapon violations, and it performs better when it comes to 90% to 100% risk category, as is shown in the graph and table above. I believe that my risk predictive model provides more robust targeting tool for allocating police resources than the traditional kernel density one.

However, there are still selection bias which have not been removed in my model. For instance, my predicting model overpredicted weapon violations in the mainly non-white area and underpredict this crime in the white-majority area. This selection bias may lead to unfairness and overpolicing when the police allocate their enforcement. Therefore, I believe it is not accurate enough for practical use.
